===Commercial performance===
The game along with ''Mickey's Runaway Zoo'' and ''Goofy's Railway Express'' sold around 400,000 copies in a year of their development.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tsden.com/articles_wwhistory.htm |title=Westwood Studios Profile |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20000816071533/http://www.tsden.com/articles_wwhistory.htm |archive-date=2000-08-16 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Amiga version was showcased at the 1990 Summer [[Consumer Electronics Show]].<ref name="DAC-Run"/> By April 1991, the Amiga version became one of the top 10 selling products in the UK.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=The April Charts from Centresoft |url=https://archive.org/stream/zzap64-magazine-072/ZZap_64_Issue_072_1991_Apr#page/n5 |magazine=[[Zzap!64]] |issue=72 |publisher=[[Newsfield]] |date=April 1991 |page=7}}</ref> By October 1991, the game was showcased at the annual [[Windhoek Show]] as part of Schoemans Office Systems.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.namibian.com.na/archive_pdf_19851990/1991_TheNamibian/8%20October%201991.pdf |title=Disney Software for Home Computers |date=October 8, 1991 |newspaper=[[The Namibian]] |access-date=August 6, 2019 |language=en-US}}</ref> Of the 25 computer Disney Software games around 1993, "Donald's Alphabet" chase was among the most successful.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1993-05-25-fi-39510-story.html |title=World Is Small So Far for Disney Software |last=Apodaca |first=Patrice |date=May 25, 1993 |newspaper=LA Times |access-date=August 6, 2019 |language=en-US}}</ref>

